2 Background

Key question: Does HEATR3 bind to RPL11 in A549 cells?

Experiment design

Condition 1: myc-tagged HEATR3-transduced A549 cell line, followed by IP using myc antibody
Condition 2: empty GFP vector-transduced A549 cell line, followed by IP using myc antibody

3 The MS data

All MS data are stored in four Excel sheets, each of which contains the two sheets processed full list and Unprocessed proteinGroups.

fn <- c("Exp2 sample 1.xlsx", "Exp2 sample 2.xlsx", "Exp3.xlsx", "Exp4.xlsx");

We load unprocessed data into a list of dataframes.

data.list <- lapply(fn, function(x) as.data.frame(read_excel(x, sheet = 2)));
names(data.list) <- gsub(".xlsx", "", fn);
names(data.list) <- gsub(" ", "_", names(data.list));
As an example, we show data from Exp3.xlsx in the following table:

4 Data cleaning

From every dataframe in the list, we extract LFQ intensities for the GFP and Myc-tagged (MT) libraries

data <- lapply(data.list, function(x) {
  df <- x[, c(1, 2, 17)];
  colnames(df) <- c("GFP", "MT", "proteinID");
  return(df);
})

and merge all dataframes from the list into one dataframe.

data.merged <- Reduce(function(x,y) merge(x, y, by = "proteinID", all = TRUE), data);
## Warning in merge.data.frame(x, y, by = "proteinID", all = TRUE): column
## names 'GFP.x', 'MT.x', 'GFP.y', 'MT.y' are duplicated in the result
# Give unique colnames
colnames(data.merged) <- c("proteinID", paste(rep(c("GFP", "MT"), 4), rep(names(data), each = 2), sep = "_"));
# Replace zeros with NA's
data.merged[data.merged == 0] <- NA;

5 Replicate library consistency

We plot pairwise sample log2-transformed LFQ values, and show corresponding Pearsons product-moment correlation coefficients. Congruence between replicate libraries is reflected by large positive correlation coefficients. Dashed red lines indicate the identity map, and blue lines with blue shaded areas give the linear model fit including 95% confidence intervals.

6 GFP-corrected replicate library consistency

We calculate relative protein abundances as \[ \text{relLog2LFQ} = \log_2(\text{LFQ, MT}) - \log_2(\text{LFQ, GFP})\,, \] and show pairwise comparisons.

7 Discussion

Pairwise comparisons of protein abundances in the myc-tagged and GFP libraries show large congruence within myc-tagged replicates and within GFP libraries. However, the large correlation coefficients when comparing protein abundances from myc-tagged with GFP libraries suggest that specific binding using the myc antibodies is low.
